essed by the join operation.\n3. **Apply AGGREGATE_FILTER_TRANSPOSE**: Push the aggregate operation below the filter if it results in processing fewer rows.\n\n### Transformed Query:\nAfter applying the selected rules, the query can be rewritten as follows:\n\n```sql\nselect\n    100.00 * sum(l_extendedprice * (1 - l_discount)) filter (where p_type like \'PROMO%\') / sum(l_extendedprice * (1 - l_discount)) as promo_revenue\nfrom\n    (select * from lineitem where l_shipdate >= date \'1996-02-01\' and l_shipdate < date \'1996-02-01\' + interval \'1\' month) l\njoin\n    part p on l.l_partkey = p.p_partkey\nlimit 1;\n```\n\n### Selected Query Rewrite Rules:\n```python\n[\n    "AGGREGATE_CASE_TO_FILTER",\n    "FILTER_INTO_JOIN",\n    "AGGREGATE_FILTER_TRANSPOSE"\n]\n```\n\nThese steps and rules should help in optimizing the query by simplifying the aggregation logic and reducing the number of rows processed during the join operation.', 'time': 4.858197927474976}
